is a work of science, it does not ignore the social component. Wilson looks at low-income areas that have poor vegetation, and shows how enhancing these areas through the planting of community gardens and trees can alleviate social ills. This book will be essential reading for environmentalists and anyone making decisions for the nature and well-being of our cities and citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnvironmental health. 0aUrban climatology. 0aUrban ecology (Biology). 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aurbanization, environment, nature, open spaces, green space, parks, gardens, vegetation, trees, temperature, weather, global warming, climate change, science, ground water, conservation, preservation, community garden, poverty, urban, city, environmentalism, ecology, climatology, environmental health, population, nonfiction, land use, streamwater, rainfall, reservoirs, sediment, energy, carbon, evapotranspiration, vocs, ozone, wealth, mortality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226901473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226901473/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles